<paragraph id="8BDB5F390A77FFA8E5CEFF723B37A4C7" blockId="61.[156,772,195,738]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis id="B910832B0A77FFA8E5CEFF723B00A6FD" box="[156,275,195,216]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The 
<taxonomicName id="4C6424BA0A77FFA8E432FF723BF6A6FC" authority="Armbruster, 2004" authorityName="Armbruster" authorityYear="2004" box="[352,485,195,217]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="61" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" status="NEW TRIBE" tribe="Rhinelepini">Rhinelepini</taxonomicName>
is diagnosed by two unique characteristics: an upper pharyngeal tooth plate with a lateral shelf (31: 1) and a large, U-shaped, two-part diverticulum of the digestive tract (211: 1-3). Other characteristics considered synapomorphic for the 
<taxonomicName id="4C6424BA0A77FFA8E599FEED3B43A757" authority="Armbruster, 2004" authorityName="Armbruster" authorityYear="2004" box="[203,336,348,370]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="61" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" status="NEW TRIBE" tribe="Rhinelepini">Rhinelepini</taxonomicName>
are: loss of the second basibranchial (3: 2), interhyal not contacting the cartilaginous section between the hyomandibula and quadrate (26: 0), a long ventromesial process of the palatine (59: 1), a very large, almost square nasal (105: 2), a flattened and widened parasphenoid (106: 1), a loss of ribs behind the enlarged rib of the sixth vertebral centrum (129: 1), at least a partial exposure of the coracoid strut (162: 0), circular (vs. bilobed) pupils, and a straight oesophagus to which the intestine does not pass dorsally (210: 1). See description and diagnosis of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C6424BA0A77FFA8E594FD1C3B58A4E6" authority="Armbruster, 2004" authorityName="Armbruster" authorityYear="2004" box="[198,331,685,707]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="61" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" status="NEW TRIBE" tribe="Rhinelepini">Rhinelepini</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF522C80A77FFA8E43CFD1C3843A4E6" author="Armbruster JW" box="[366,592,685,707]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="620 - 636" refId="ref45916" refString="Armbruster JW. 1998 b. Phylogenetic relationships of the suckermouth armored catfishes of the Rhinelepis group (Loricariidae: Hypostominae). Copeia 1998: 620 - 636." type="journal article" year="1998">Armbruster (1998b)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF522C80A77FFA8E7D5FD1C3B32A4C7" author="Quevedo R &amp; Reis RE" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" pagination="402 - 410" refId="ref47276" refString="Quevedo R, Reis RE. 2002. Pogonopoma obscurum: a new species of loricariid catfish (Siluriformes: Loricariidae) from southern Brazil, with comments on the genus Pogonopoma. Copeia 2002: 402 - 410." type="journal article" year="2002">Quevedo &amp; Reis (2002)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BDB5F390A77FFA8E5CEFCB13808A20C" blockId="61.[156,772,767,1065]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis id="B910832B0A77FFA8E5CEFCB13B24A530" box="[156,311,768,789]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Comparisons:</emphasis>
The 
<taxonomicName id="4C6424BA0A77FFA8E42EFD4E3812A530" authority="Armbruster, 2004" authorityName="Armbruster" authorityYear="2004" box="[380,513,767,789]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="61" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" status="NEW TRIBE" tribe="Rhinelepini">Rhinelepini</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C6424BA0A77FFA8E58AFCAF3B9DA516" authorityName="Eigenmann" authorityYear="1909" box="[216,398,798,819]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Corymbophanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910832B0A77FFA8E58AFCAF3B9DA516" box="[216,398,798,819]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Corymbophanes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the lack of a postdorsal ridge of three or more median preadipose plates, and by having five (vs. three) rows of plates on the caudal peduncle, from the 
<taxonomicName id="4C6424BA0A77FFA8E427FCCB3814A5B5" authorityName="Kner" authorityYear="1853" box="[373,519,890,912]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="61" pageNumber="60" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Hypostomini">Hypostomini</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName id="4C6424BA0A77FFA8E738FCCB3AC0A58A" authorityName="Armbruster" authorityYear="2004" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Pterygoplichthini">Pterygoplichthini</taxonomicName>
by having one unbranched and five branched anal-fin rays (vs. one unbranched and four branched rays) and by lacking the dorsal flap of the iris, and from the 
<taxonomicName id="4C6424BA0A77FFA8E456FC443B65A22E" authorityName="Kner" authorityYear="1853" box="[260,374,1013,1035]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Ancistrini">Ancistrini</taxonomicName>
and the 
<taxonomicName id="4C6424BA0A77FFA8E489FC4438B0A22E" authorityName="Armbruster" authorityYear="2004" box="[475,675,1013,1035]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Chordata" rank="tribe" tribe="Pterygoplichthini">Pterygoplichthini</taxonomicName>
by lacking highly evertible cheek plates.
</paragraph>
